ord_wuf <- ord$weighted_unifrac$data # weighted UniFrac distance based PCoA

2 Ordination

Unweighted beta-diversity distance metrics such as unweighted UniFrac are subjective to technical noises, making comparison of results across studies difficult (Wong et al., 2016; Nearing et al., 2018). Here we use weighted distance metrics including robust Aitchison distance and weighted UniFrac distance to compare beta-diversity. Robust Aitchison distance is a compositional beta diversity metric rooted in a centered log-ratio (CLR) transformation and matrix completion (Martino et al., 2019). It has some desirable properties: 1)scale invariant, which ensures equivalence between distances computed from absolute and relative abundance measurements, negating the need to perform rarefaction; 2)relative changes driven. Microbes that display large fold change across samples will be weighted more heavily, which makes the ordination robust to random fluctuations of high-abundant taxa; 3)sub-compositionally coherent, which guarantees that distances will never decrease if additional taxa are observed.

2.1 PCoA: robust Aitchison distance

pcoa_atch <- ord_atch$Vectors %>% 
  mutate(
    SampleID = as.character(SampleID),
    SampleID = ifelse(nchar(SampleID) < 2, paste0("0", SampleID), SampleID)
    ) %>% 
  inner_join(mtd, by = "SampleID") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = PC1, y = PC2, color = Population, shape = Environment)) +
    geom_hline(yintercept = 0, color = "grey") +
    geom_vline(xintercept = 0, color = "grey") +
    # data ellipse
    stat_ellipse(linetype = "dashed") +
    geom_point(size = 2) +
    # keep the aspect ratio between y and x axis (y-axis/x-axis)
    coord_fixed(ord_atch$ProportionExplained[2]/ord_atch$ProportionExplained[1]) + 
    labs(
      x = paste0("PCo1: ", round(100 * ord_atch$ProportionExplained[1], 1), "%"),
      y = paste0("PCo2: ", round(100 * ord_atch$ProportionExplained[2], 1), "%")
      ) +
    scale_color_brewer(palette = "Set2") +
    theme_bw(base_size = 14)

pcoa_atch + labs(title = "PCoA of robust Aitchison distance")

3 PERMANVOA

3.1 Export distance matrix

We export the distance matrices and run PERMANOVA using the PERMANOVA+ add-on from the PRIMER v7.

# combine distance matrices into a list 
dist_list <- list(dist_atch, dist_wuf)
names(dist_list) <- c("Aitchison_distance", "Weighted_UniFrac_distance")

# export distance matrices
lapply(seq_along(dist_list), function(x) {
  dist_list[[x]] %>%
    as.matrix() %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    write.table( 
      here(
        paste0("data/intermediate/permanova/tilapia/", names(dist_list)[x], ".tsv")
        ), 
      sep = "\t", 
      col.names = NA, 
      row.names = TRUE)
    }
  )

3.2 Import and format PERMANVOA results

# import permanova results
permanova <- read_csv(
  here("data/intermediate/permanova/tilapia/permanova_results.csv")
  )

# format permanova results
permanova %>% 
  # the following 4 lines of code adjust raw p values
  group_nest(Distance, Comparison) %>%
  mutate(P_adj = map(data, ~p.adjust(.x$P, method = "holm"))) %>%
  unnest(cols = c(data, P_adj)) %>%
  ungroup() %>%
  mutate(
    Comparison = gsub(
      "Tilapia_farmed_pond - Tilapia_farmed_lake", 
      "farmed tilapia", 
      Comparison
      ),
    Comparison = gsub(
      "Tilapia_farmed_lake - Tilapia_wild_lake", 
      "tilapia in lake", 
      Comparison
      ),
    Comparison = factor(
      Comparison, levels = c("farmed tilapia", "tilapia in lake")
      ),
    Term = gsub("Environment", "Environment (Pond vs Lake)", Term),
    Term = gsub("Population", "Population (Farmed vs Wild)", Term),
    P = P_adj
    ) %>%
  select(-P_adj) %>%
  arrange(Distance, Comparison) %>%
  flextable() %>%
  set_caption(
    caption = "Table 1. PERMANOVA results based on robust Aitchison and weighted UniFrac distance."
    ) %>%
  autofit() %>%
  italic(j = 5:6, italic = TRUE, part = "head") %>% # italicize column names
  merge_v(j = c("Distance", "Comparison")) %>% # merge cells by phylum
  theme_booktabs() %>% # apply table style
  align(align = "left", part = "all") %>% # align text to the left
  hline(i = c(3, 6, 9), part = "body") # draw horizontal lines

4 PERMDISP

PERMANOVA tests differences in both location and dispersion effects. Although PERMANOVA is robust to heterogeneity in the multivariate dispersion, its a good practice to look at the homogeneity of multivariate dispersion following a significant PERMANVOA result. The homogeneity of multivariate dispersion can be assessed visually (PCoA plot/boxplot) or by a permutation test called PERMDISP, which is implemented in R by the betadisper() function from the vegan package. When within-group sample sizes are small (n < 5), formal testing with PERMDISP is not very meaningful. Visual assessment is a better option.

4.1 Robust Aitchison distance

4.1.1 Farmed tilapia: pond vs lake

Subset distance matrix.

mtd_farmed <- filter(mtd, Population == "Farmed") %>%
  mutate(Site = paste0(Environment, "_", Site))

dist_atch_farmed <- dist_subset(dist_atch, mtd_farmed$SampleID)

4.1.1.1 Site-level

First, we check the equality of dispersion for samples (replicates) across different Site (centroids).

Compute beta-dispersion.

(
disp_atch_farmed_site <- betadisper(
  d = dist_atch_farmed, 
  group = mtd_farmed$Site, 
  type = "median", 
  bias.adjust = TRUE
  )
)
## 
##  Homogeneity of multivariate dispersions

plot_betadisper(
  disp_atch_farmed_site,

  coord_flip()

4.1.1.2 Environment-level

Next, we consider differences in the dispersion of Site centroids around the Environment centroids.

Compute distance among the Site centroids.

dist_atch_farmed_site <- dist_multi_centroids(dist_atch_farmed, mtd_farmed$Site)

Make a new metadata matching Site and Environment.

mtd_farmed_site <- mtd_farmed %>%
  select(Environment, Site) %>%
  distinct()%>%
  arrange(Site)

Compute beta-dispersion.
